1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,489
I'm a diabetic.

2
00:00:01,680 --> 00:00:07,009
Right after I discovered I had this ailment, about 5,000 hypodermics ago,

3
00:00:07,120 --> 00:00:15,249
I was warned, Diabetes is a physical condition, but the biggest damage results from having a negative attitude about it.

4
00:00:15,520 --> 00:00:18,609
Worry about it, and you may have real trouble.

5
00:00:19,280 --> 00:00:25,889
Naturally, since the discovery of my own diabetes, I've gotten to know a great many other diabetics.

6
00:00:26,160 --> 00:00:28,850
Let me tell you about two extremes.

7
00:00:29,200 --> 00:00:34,930
One fellow who has a very mild case belongs to that fraternity of the living dead.

8
00:00:35,200 --> 00:00:40,050
Obsessed with the fear of the weather, he is usually ridiculously bundled up.

9
00:00:40,240 --> 00:00:45,570
He's afraid of infection, so he shuns anybody who has the slightest sniffle.

10
00:00:45,760 --> 00:00:49,650
He's afraid of overexertion, so he does almost nothing.

11
00:00:49,840 --> 00:00:54,210
He spends most of his mental energy worrying about what might happen.

12
00:00:54,480 --> 00:00:59,090
He bores other people, telling them how awful his problem really is.

13
00:00:59,440 --> 00:01:02,210
His real ailment is not diabetes.

14
00:01:02,480 --> 00:01:05,729
Rather, he's a victim of health excusitis.

15
00:01:05,920 --> 00:01:09,330
He has pitied himself into being an invalid.

16
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:14,369
The other extreme is a division manager for a large publishing company.

17
00:01:14,560 --> 00:01:16,369
He has a severe case.

18
00:01:16,480 --> 00:01:21,170
He takes about thirty times as much insulin as the fellow just mentioned.

19
00:01:21,280 --> 00:01:23,810
But he is not living to be sick.

20
00:01:24,080 --> 00:01:27,249
He is living to enjoy his work and have fun.

21
00:01:27,600 --> 00:01:33,009
One day he said to me, Sure, it is an inconvenience, but so is shaving.

22
00:01:33,040 --> 00:01:35,970
But I'm not going to think myself to bed.

23
00:01:36,080 --> 00:01:40,850
When I take those shots, I just praise the guys who discovered insulin.

24
00:01:41,520 --> 00:01:49,009
A good friend of mine, a widely known college educator, came home from Europe in 1945, minus one arm.

25
00:01:49,280 --> 00:01:54,290
Despite his handicap, John is always smiling, always helping others.

26
00:01:54,480 --> 00:01:57,650
He's about as optimistic as anyone I know.

27
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:01,570
One day, he and I had a long talk about his handicap.

28
00:02:02,080 --> 00:02:04,050
It's just an arm," he said.

29
00:02:04,240 --> 00:02:09,009
Sure, two are better than one, but they just cut off my arm.

30
00:02:09,120 --> 00:02:11,970
My spirit is one hundred percent intact.

31
00:02:12,160 --> 00:02:13,970
I'm really grateful for that.

32
00:02:14,640 --> 00:02:17,889
Another amputee friend is an excellent golfer.

33
00:02:18,080 --> 00:02:24,450
One day I asked him how he had been able to develop such a near-perfect style with just one arm.

34
00:02:24,720 --> 00:02:29,170
I mentioned that most golfers with two arms can't do nearly as well.

35
00:02:29,360 --> 00:02:31,249
His reply says a lot.

36
00:02:31,680 --> 00:02:41,009
Well, it's my experience, he said, that the right attitude and one arm will beat the wrong attitude and two arms every time.

37
00:02:41,520 --> 00:02:47,410
The right attitude and one arm will beat the wrong attitude and two arms every time.

38
00:02:47,600 --> 00:02:49,249
Think about that for a while.

